text:
Park Avenue (called Fourth Avenue until about 1890) north from about 105th Street, showing two track railroad on wooden trestle.

The little wooded hill in right background is the future Mt. Morris Park. The deepest part of the old Harlem Creek bed is between 106th and 107th Streets. For some reason Drips' Plan of New York for 1867 and for 1868 utterly fails to show the big building in the center of the picture, which should be at about 110th Street and Fifth Avenue, nor any of the buildings just west of Fourth Avenue around 110th Street except the five small houses nearest the camera, on the S.W. corner of 110th Street. The steeple on the horizon to the right is probably the Mt. Morris Baptist Church at Fifth Avenue near 126th Street; this is, however, only a guess.

This photograph was used as an illustration in the first of Henry Collins Brown's Valentine's Manuals, 1916-17, opposite page 91.

1860.

New York Edison Company Collection.

Neg # 464

East 105th Street, south side, east from, but not including Park, to and including Madison Aves. In the immediate foreground, is a synagogue Beth Hamidrash Hagodol of Harlem (No. 110), with the Hebrew Home for the Aged (Nos. 114-118) adjoining. P.S. No. 72 Annex is shown adjoining the S.N. corner of Lexington Ave.
August 31, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
NEG #3422

Park Avenue, west side, north from and including 1422 Park Avenue, between 105th and 106th Streets. The sign reads "Fish Market" twice, once in English and once in Hebrew characters.
July 6, 1934.
L. Sperr.
